# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: retrieval-rerankers
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:retrieval-rerankers/cosine-similarity] In data analysis, **cosine similarity** is a measure of similarity between two non-zero vectors defined in an inner product space.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/cosine-similarity] Cosine similarity is the cosine of the angle between the vectors; that is, it is the dot product of the vectors divided by the product of their lengths.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/cosine-similarity] It follows that the cosine similarity does not depend on the magnitudes of the vectors, but only on their angle.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/cosine-similarity] The cosine similarity always belongs to the interval $[-1,+1].$ For example, two proportional vectors have a cosine similarity of +1, two orthogonal vectors have a similarity of 0, and two opposite vectors have a similarity of −1.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/cosine-similarity] In some contexts, the component values of the vectors cannot be negative, in which case the cosine similarity is bounded in $[0,1]$ .
[src:retrieval-rerankers/cosine-similarity] For example, in information retrieval and text mining, each word is assigned a different coordinate and a document is represented by the vector of the numbers of occurrences of each word in the document.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/cosine-similarity] Cosine similarity then gives a useful measure of how similar two documents are likely to be, in terms of their subject matter, and independently of the length of the documents.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/cosine-similarity] The technique is also used to measure cohesion within clusters in the field of data mining.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/cosine-similarity] One advantage of cosine similarity is its low complexity, especially for sparse vectors: only the non-zero coordinates need to be considered.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/cosine-similarity] Other names for cosine similarity include **Orchini similarity** and **Tucker coefficient of congruence**; the **Otsuka–Ochiai similarity** (see below) is cosine similarity applied to binary data.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/cosine-similarity] where $A_{i}$ and $B_{i}$ are the i th components of vectors $\mathbf {A}$ and $\mathbf {B}$ , respectively.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/cosine-similarity] The resulting similarity ranges from −1 meaning exactly opposite, to +1 meaning exactly the same, with 0 indicating orthogonality (no correlation), while in-between values indicate intermediate similarity or dissimilarity.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/cosine-similarity] For text matching, the attribute vectors *A* and *B* are usually the term frequency vectors of the documents.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/cosine-similarity] Cosine similarity can be seen as a method of normalizing document length during comparison.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/cosine-similarity] In the case of information retrieval, the cosine similarity of two documents will range from $0\to 1$ , since the term frequencies cannot be negative.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/cosine-similarity] This remains true when using TF-IDF weights.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/cosine-similarity] The angle between two term frequency vectors cannot be greater than 90°.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/cosine-similarity] If the attribute vectors are normalized by subtracting the vector means (e.g., $A-{\bar {A}}$ ), the measure is called the centered cosine similarity and is equivalent to the Pearson correlation coefficient.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/cosine-similarity] By virtue of being proportional to squared Euclidean distance, the cosine distance is not a true distance metric; it does not exhibit the triangle inequality property — or, more formally, the Schwarz inequality — and it violates the coincidence axiom.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/cosine-similarity] To repair the triangle inequality property while maintaining the same ordering, one can convert to Euclidean distance ${\textstyle {\sqrt {2(1-S_{C}(A,B))}}}$ or angular distance *θ* = arccos(*S**C*(*A*, *B*)).
[src:retrieval-rerankers/cosine-similarity] Alternatively, the triangular inequality that does work for angular distances can be expressed directly in terms of the cosines; see below.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/cosine-similarity] The normalized angle, referred to as **angular distance**, between any two vectors A and B is a formal distance metric and can be calculated from the cosine similarity.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/cosine-similarity] The complement of the angular distance metric can then be used to define **angular similarity** function bounded between 0 and 1, inclusive.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/cosine-similarity] Unfortunately, computing the inverse cosine (arccos) function is slow, making the use of the angular distance more computationally expensive than using the more common (but not metric) cosine distance above.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/cosine-similarity] Another effective proxy for cosine distance can be obtained by $L_{2}$ normalisation of the vectors, followed by the application of normal Euclidean distance.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/cosine-similarity] Using this technique each term in each vector is first divided by the magnitude of the vector, yielding a vector of unit length.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/cosine-similarity] Once the normalisation has occurred, the vector space can be used with the full range of techniques available to any Euclidean space, notably standard dimensionality reduction techniques.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/cosine-similarity] This normalised form distance is often used within many deep learning algorithms.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/cosine-similarity] Here, A and B are sets, and $|A|$ is the number of elements in A .
[src:retrieval-rerankers/cosine-similarity] If sets are represented as bit vectors, the Otsuka–Ochiai coefficient can be seen to be the same as the cosine similarity.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/cosine-similarity] It is identical to the score introduced by Godfrey Thomson.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/cosine-similarity] In a recent book, the coefficient is tentatively misattributed to another Japanese researcher with the family name Otsuka.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/cosine-similarity] The confusion arises because in 1957 Akira Ochiai attributes the coefficient only to Otsuka (no first name mentioned) by citing an article by Ikuso Hamai (Japanese: 浜井 生三), who in turn cites the original 1936 article by Yanosuke Otsuka.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/cosine-similarity] The most noteworthy property of cosine similarity is that it reflects a relative, rather than absolute, comparison of the individual vector dimensions.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/cosine-similarity] For any positive constant a and vector V , the vectors V and $aV$ are maximally similar.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/cosine-similarity] The measure is thus most appropriate for data where frequency is more important than absolute values; notably, term frequency in documents.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/cosine-similarity] However more recent metrics with a grounding in information theory, such as Jensen–Shannon, SED, and triangular divergence have been shown to have improved semantics in at least some contexts.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/cosine-similarity] Cosine similarity is related to Euclidean distance as follows.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/cosine-similarity] The Euclidean distance is called the *chord distance* (because it is the length of the chord on the unit circle) and it is the Euclidean distance between the vectors which were normalized to unit sum of squared values within them.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/cosine-similarity] This form of the triangle inequality can be used to bound the minimum and maximum similarity of two objects A and B if the similarities to a reference object C is already known.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/cosine-similarity] This is used for example in metric data indexing, but has also been used to accelerate spherical k-means clustering the same way the Euclidean triangle inequality has been used to accelerate regular k-means.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/cosine-similarity] A soft cosine or ("soft" similarity) between two vectors considers similarities between pairs of features.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/cosine-similarity] For example, in the field of natural language processing (NLP) the similarity among features is quite intuitive.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/cosine-similarity] Features such as words, *n*-grams, or syntactic *n*-grams can be quite similar, though formally they are considered as different features in the VSM.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/cosine-similarity] For example, words "play" and "game" are different words and thus mapped to different points in VSM; yet they are semantically related.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/cosine-similarity] In case of *n*-grams or syntactic *n*-grams, Levenshtein distance can be applied (in fact, Levenshtein distance can be applied to words as well).
[src:retrieval-rerankers/cosine-similarity] For calculating soft cosine, the matrix **s** is used to indicate similarity between features.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/cosine-similarity] It can be calculated through Levenshtein distance, WordNet similarity, or other similarity measures.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/cosine-similarity] where *sij* = similarity(feature*i*, feature*j*).
[src:retrieval-rerankers/cosine-similarity] If there is no similarity between features (*sii* = 1, *sij* = 0 for *i* ≠ *j*), the given equation is equivalent to the conventional cosine similarity formula.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/cosine-similarity] The time complexity of this measure is quadratic, which makes it applicable to real-world tasks.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/cosine-similarity] Note that the complexity can be reduced to subquadratic.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/cosine-similarity] An efficient implementation of such soft cosine similarity is included in the Gensim open source library.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] Ranking is a central part of many information retrieval problems, such as document retrieval, collaborative filtering, sentiment analysis, and online advertising.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] A possible architecture of a machine-learned search engine is shown in the accompanying figure.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] Training data consists of queries and documents matching them together with the relevance degree of each match.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] It may be prepared manually by human *assessors* (or *raters*, as Google calls them), who check results for some queries and determine relevance of each result.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] It is not feasible to check the relevance of all documents, and so typically a technique called pooling is used — only the top few documents, retrieved by some existing ranking models are checked.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] This technique may introduce selection bias.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] Alternatively, training data may be derived automatically by analyzing *clickthrough logs* (i.e. search results which got clicks from users), *query chains*, or such search engines' features as Google's (since-replaced) SearchWiki.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] Clickthrough logs can be biased by the tendency of users to click on the top search results on the assumption that they are already well-ranked.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] Training data is used by a learning algorithm to produce a ranking model which computes the relevance of documents for actual queries.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] Typically, users expect a search query to complete in a short time (such as a few hundred milliseconds for web search), which makes it impossible to evaluate a complex ranking model on each document in the corpus, and so a two-phase scheme is used.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] First, a small number of potentially relevant documents are identified using simpler retrieval models which permit fast query evaluation, such as the vector space model, Boolean model, weighted AND, or BM25.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] This phase is called *top- k document retrieval* and many heuristics were proposed in the literature to accelerate it, such as using a document's static quality score and tiered indexes.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] In the second phase, a more accurate but computationally expensive machine-learned model is used to re-rank these documents.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] For the convenience of MLR algorithms, query-document pairs are usually represented by numerical vectors, which are called *feature vectors*.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] Such an approach is sometimes called *bag of features* and is analogous to the bag of words model and vector space model used in information retrieval for representation of documents.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] Components of such vectors are called *features*, *factors* or *ranking signals*.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] Selecting and designing good features is an important area in machine learning, which is called feature engineering.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] There are several measures (metrics) which are commonly used to judge how well an algorithm is doing on training data and to compare the performance of different MLR algorithms.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] Often a learning-to-rank problem is reformulated as an optimization problem with respect to one of these metrics.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] DCG and its normalized variant NDCG are usually preferred in academic research when multiple levels of relevance are used.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] Other metrics such as MAP, MRR and precision, are defined only for binary judgments.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] Both of these metrics are based on the assumption that the user is more likely to stop looking at search results after examining a more relevant document, than after a less relevant document.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] Learning to Rank approaches are often categorized using one of three approaches: pointwise (where individual documents are ranked), pairwise (where pairs of documents are ranked into a relative order), and listwise (where an entire list of documents are ordered).
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] Tie-Yan Liu of Microsoft Research Asia has analyzed existing algorithms for learning to rank problems in his book *Learning to Rank for Information Retrieval*.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] He categorized them into three groups by their input spaces, output spaces, hypothesis spaces (the core function of the model) and loss functions: the pointwise, pairwise, and listwise approach.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] In practice, listwise approaches often outperform pairwise approaches and pointwise approaches.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] This statement was further supported by a large scale experiment on the performance of different learning-to-rank methods on a large collection of benchmark data sets.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] In this section, without further notice, x denotes an object to be evaluated, for example, a document or an image, $f(x)$ denotes a single-value hypothesis, $h(\cdot )$ denotes a bi-variate or multi-variate function and $L(\cdot )$ denotes the loss function.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] In this case, it is assumed that each query-document pair in the training data has a numerical or ordinal score.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] Then the learning-to-rank problem can be approximated by a regression problem — given a single query-document pair, predict its score.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] Formally speaking, the pointwise approach aims at learning a function $f(x)$ predicting the real-value or ordinal score of a document x using the loss function $L(f;x_{j},y_{j})$ .
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] A number of existing supervised machine learning algorithms can be readily used for this purpose.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] Ordinal regression and classification algorithms can also be used in pointwise approach when they are used to predict the score of a single query-document pair, and it takes a small, finite number of values.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] In this case, the learning-to-rank problem is approximated by a classification problem — learning a binary classifier $h(x_{u},x_{v})$ that can tell which document is better in a given pair of documents.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] The classifier shall take two documents as its input and the goal is to minimize a loss function $L(h;x_{u},x_{v},y_{u,v})$ .
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] The loss function typically reflects the number and magnitude of inversions in the induced ranking.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] In many cases, the binary classifier $h(x_{u},x_{v})$ is implemented with a scoring function $f(x)$ .
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] where ${\text{CDF}}(\cdot )$ is a cumulative distribution function, for example, the standard logistic CDF, i.e.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] These algorithms try to directly optimize the value of one of the above evaluation measures, averaged over all queries in the training data.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] This is often difficult in practice because most evaluation measures are not continuous functions with respect to ranking model's parameters, and so continuous approximations or bounds on evaluation measures have to be used.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] LambdaMART is a pairwise algorithm which has been empirically shown to approximate listwise objective functions.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] Note: as most supervised learning-to-rank algorithms can be applied to pointwise, pairwise and listwise case, only those methods which are specifically designed with ranking in mind are shown above.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] Norbert Fuhr introduced the general idea of MLR in 1992, describing learning approaches in information retrieval as a generalization of parameter estimation; a specific variant of this approach (using polynomial regression) had been published by him three years earlier.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] Bill Cooper proposed logistic regression for the same purpose in 1992 and used it with his Berkeley research group to train a successful ranking function for TREC.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] Manning et al. suggest that these early works achieved limited results in their time due to little available training data and poor machine learning techniques.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] Several conferences, such as NeurIPS, SIGIR and ICML have had workshops devoted to the learning-to-rank problem since the mid-2000s (decade).
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] Commercial web search engines began using machine-learned ranking systems since the 2000s (decade).
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] One of the first search engines to start using it was AltaVista (later its technology was acquired by Overture, and then Yahoo), which launched a gradient boosting-trained ranking function in April 2003.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] At its launch in 2009, Microsoft Bing's search engine was powered by the RankNet algorithm, which was invented at Microsoft Research in 2005.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] In November 2009 a Russian search engine Yandex announced that it had significantly increased its search quality due to deployment of a new proprietary MatrixNet algorithm, a variant of gradient boosting method which uses oblivious decision trees.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] Recently they have also sponsored a machine-learned ranking competition "Internet Mathematics 2009" based on their own search engine's production data.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] Yahoo has announced a similar competition in 2010.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] As of 2008, Google's Peter Norvig denied that their search engine exclusively relies on machine-learned ranking.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] In January 2017, the technology was included in the open source search engine Apache Solr.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] It is also available in the open source OpenSearch and Elasticsearch.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] These implementations make learning to rank widely accessible for enterprise search.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] Similar to recognition applications in computer vision, recent neural network based ranking algorithms are also found to be susceptible to covert adversarial attacks, both on the candidates and the queries.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] With small perturbations imperceptible to human beings, ranking order could be arbitrarily altered.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] In addition, model-agnostic transferable adversarial examples are found to be possible, which enables black-box adversarial attacks on deep ranking systems without requiring access to their underlying implementations.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/learning-to-rank] Conversely, the robustness of such ranking systems can be improved via adversarial defenses such as the Madry defense.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] Formally, the nearest neighbor (NN) search problem is defined as follows: given a set S of points in a space M and a query point $q\in M$ , find the closest point in S to q.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] Donald Knuth in volume 3 of *The Art of Computer Programming* (1973) called it the **post-office problem**, referring to an application of assigning to a residence the nearest post office.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] A direct generalization of this problem is a k-NN search, where we need to find the k closest points.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] Most commonly M is a metric space and dissimilarity is expressed as a distance metric, which is symmetric and satisfies the triangle inequality.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] Even more common, M is taken to be the d-dimensional vector space where dissimilarity is measured using the Euclidean distance, Manhattan distance or other distance metric.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] However, the dissimilarity function can be arbitrary.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] One example is asymmetric Bregman divergence, for which the triangle inequality does not hold.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] Various solutions to the NNS problem have been proposed.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] The quality and usefulness of the algorithms are determined by the time complexity of queries as well as the space complexity of any search data structures that must be maintained.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] The informal observation usually referred to as the curse of dimensionality states that there is no general-purpose exact solution for NNS in high-dimensional Euclidean space using polynomial preprocessing and polylogarithmic search time.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] The simplest solution to the NNS problem is to compute the distance from the query point to every other point in the database, keeping track of the "best so far".
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] This algorithm, sometimes referred to as the naive approach, has a running time of *O*(*dN*), where *N* is the cardinality of *S* and *d* is the dimensionality of *S*.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] There are no search data structures to maintain, so the linear search has no space complexity beyond the storage of the database.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] Naive search can, on average, outperform space partitioning approaches on higher dimensional spaces.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] The absolute distance is not required for distance comparison, only the relative distance.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] In geometric coordinate systems the distance calculation can be sped up considerably by omitting the square root calculation from the distance calculation between two coordinates.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] The distance comparison will still yield identical results.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] Since the 1970s, the branch and bound methodology has been applied to the problem.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] In the case of Euclidean space, this approach encompasses spatial index or spatial access methods.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] Several space-partitioning methods have been developed for solving the NNS problem.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] Perhaps the simplest is the k-d tree, which iteratively bisects the search space into two regions containing half of the points of the parent region.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] Queries are performed via traversal of the tree from the root to a leaf by evaluating the query point at each split.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] Depending on the distance specified in the query, neighboring branches that might contain hits may also need to be evaluated.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] R-trees can yield nearest neighbors not only for Euclidean distance, but can also be used with other distances.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] In the case of general metric space, the branch-and-bound approach is known as the metric tree approach.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] Particular examples include vp-tree and BK-tree methods.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] Using a set of points taken from a 3-dimensional space and put into a BSP tree, and given a query point taken from the same space, a possible solution to the problem of finding the nearest point-cloud point to the query point is given in the following description of an algorithm.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] (Strictly speaking, no such point may exist, because it may not be unique.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] This may not be the case, but it is a good heuristic.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] After having recursively gone through all the trouble of solving the problem for the guessed half-space, now compare the distance returned by this result with the shortest distance from the query point to the partitioning plane.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] This latter distance is that between the query point and the closest possible point that could exist in the half-space not searched.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] If this distance is greater than that returned in the earlier result, then clearly there is no need to search the other half-space.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] If there is such a need, then you must go through the trouble of solving the problem for the other half space, and then compare its result to the former result, and then return the proper result.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] An approximate nearest neighbor search algorithm is allowed to return points whose distance from the query is at most c times the distance from the query to its nearest points.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] The appeal of this approach is that, in many cases, an approximate nearest neighbor is almost as good as the exact one.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] In particular, if the distance measure accurately captures the notion of user quality, then small differences in the distance should not matter.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] Proximity graph methods (such as navigable small world graphs and HNSW) are considered the current state-of-the-art for the approximate nearest neighbors search.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] The methods are based on greedy traversing in proximity neighborhood graphs $G(V,E)$ in which every point $x_{i}\in S$ is uniquely associated with vertex $v_{i}\in V$ .
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] The search for the nearest neighbors to a query *q* in the set *S* takes the form of searching for the vertex in the graph $G(V,E)$ .
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] The basic algorithm – greedy search – works as follows: search starts from an enter-point vertex $v_{i}\in V$ by computing the distances from the query q to each vertex of its neighborhood $\{v_{j}:(v_{i},v_{j})\in E\}$ , and then finds a vertex with the minimal distance value.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] If the distance value between the query and the selected vertex is smaller than the one between the query and the current element, then the algorithm moves to the selected vertex, and it becomes new enter-point.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] The algorithm stops when it reaches a local minimum: a vertex whose neighborhood does not contain a vertex that is closer to the query than the vertex itself.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] These works were preceded by a pioneering paper by Toussaint, in which he introduced the concept of a *relative neighborhood* graph.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] Locality sensitive hashing (LSH) is a technique for grouping points in space into 'buckets' based on some distance metric operating on the points.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] Points that are close to each other under the chosen metric are mapped to the same bucket with high probability.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] The cover tree has a theoretical bound that is based on the dataset's doubling constant.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] The bound on search time is *O*(*c*12 log *n*) where *c* is the expansion constant of the dataset.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] In the special case where the data is a dense 3D map of geometric points, the projection geometry of the sensing technique can be used to dramatically simplify the search problem.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] This approach requires that the 3D data is organized by a projection to a two-dimensional grid and assumes that the data is spatially smooth across neighboring grid cells with the exception of object boundaries.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] These assumptions are valid when dealing with 3D sensor data in applications such as surveying, robotics and stereo vision but may not hold for unorganized data in general.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] In practice this technique has an average search time of *O*(*1*) or *O*(*K*) for the *k*-nearest neighbor problem when applied to real world stereo vision data.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] In high-dimensional spaces, tree indexing structures become useless because an increasing percentage of the nodes need to be examined anyway.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] To speed up linear search, a compressed version of the feature vectors stored in RAM is used to prefilter the datasets in a first run.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] The final candidates are determined in a second stage using the uncompressed data from the disk for distance calculation.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] The VA-file approach is a special case of a compression based search, where each feature component is compressed uniformly and independently.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] The optimal compression technique in multidimensional spaces is Vector Quantization (VQ), implemented through clustering.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] The database is clustered and the most "promising" clusters are retrieved.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] Huge gains over VA-File, tree-based indexes and sequential scan have been observed.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] Also note the parallels between clustering and LSH.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] There are numerous variants of the NNS problem and the two most well-known are the *k*-nearest neighbor search and the ε-approximate nearest neighbor search.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] In some applications it may be acceptable to retrieve a "good guess" of the nearest neighbor.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] In those cases, we can use an algorithm which doesn't guarantee to return the actual nearest neighbor in every case, in return for improved speed or memory savings.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] Often such an algorithm will find the nearest neighbor in a majority of cases, but this depends strongly on the dataset being queried.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] Algorithms that support the approximate nearest neighbor search include locality-sensitive hashing, best bin first and balanced box-decomposition tree based search.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] Nearest neighbor distance ratio does not apply the threshold on the direct distance from the original point to the challenger neighbor but on a ratio of it depending on the distance to the previous neighbor.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] It is used in CBIR to retrieve pictures through a "query by example" using the similarity between local features.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] More generally it is involved in several matching problems.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] Fixed-radius near neighbors is the problem where one wants to efficiently find all points given in Euclidean space within a given fixed distance from a specified point.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] The distance is assumed to be fixed, but the query point is arbitrary.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] For some applications (e.g. entropy estimation), we may have *N* data-points and wish to know which is the nearest neighbor *for every one of those N points*.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] This could, of course, be achieved by running a nearest-neighbor search once for every point, but an improved strategy would be an algorithm that exploits the information redundancy between these *N* queries to produce a more efficient search.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] As a simple example: when we find the distance from point *X* to point *Y*, that also tells us the distance from point *Y* to point *X*, so the same calculation can be reused in two different queries.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/nearest-neighbor-search] Given a fixed dimension, a semi-definite positive norm (thereby including every Lp norm), and *n* points in this space, the nearest neighbour of every point can be found in *O*(*n* log *n*) time and the *m* nearest neighbours of every point can be found in *O*(*mn* log *n*) time.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/semantic-search] Some authors regard semantic search as a set of techniques for retrieving knowledge from richly structured data sources like ontologies and XML as found on the Semantic Web.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/semantic-search] Such technologies enable the formal articulation of domain knowledge at a high level of expressiveness and could enable the user to specify their intent in more detail at query time.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/semantic-search] The articulation enhances content relevance and depth by including specific places, people, or concepts relevant to the query.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/semantic-search] Tools like Google's Knowledge Graph provide structured relationships between entities to enrich query interpretation.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/semantic-search] Models like BERT and Sentence-BERT convert words or sentences into dense vectors for similarity comparison.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/semantic-search] Semantic ontologies like Web Ontology Language, Resource Description Framework, and Schema.org organize concepts and relationships, allowing systems to infer related terms and deeper meanings.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/semantic-search] Hybrid search models combine lexical retrieval (e.g., BM25) with semantic ranking using pretrained transformer models for optimal performance.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/sentence-embedding] In natural language processing, a **sentence embedding** (or document embedding) is a representation of a natural language text as a vector of numbers which encodes meaningful semantic information.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/sentence-embedding] The name stems from the initially limitations of the approach to embed sequences of text longer than a sentence, but this is not longer a limitation.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/sentence-embedding] State of the art embeddings are based on the learned hidden layer representation of dedicated sentence transformer models.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/sentence-embedding] BERT pioneered an approach involving the use of a dedicated [CLS] token prepended to the beginning of each sentence inputted into the model; the final hidden state vector of this token encodes information about the sentence and can be fine-tuned for use in sentence classification tasks.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/sentence-embedding] In practice however, BERT's sentence embedding with the [CLS] token achieves poor performance, often worse than simply averaging non-contextual word embeddings.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/sentence-embedding] SBERT later achieved superior sentence embedding performance by fine tuning BERT's [CLS] token embeddings through the usage of a siamese neural network architecture on the SNLI dataset.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/sentence-embedding] Other approaches are loosely based on the idea of distributional semantics applied to sentences.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/sentence-embedding] Skip-Thought trains an encoder-decoder structure for the task of neighboring sentences predictions; this has been shown to achieve worse performance than approaches such as InferSent or SBERT.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/sentence-embedding] An alternative direction is to aggregate word embeddings, such as those returned by Word2vec, into sentence embeddings.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/sentence-embedding] The most straightforward approach is to simply compute the average of word vectors, known as continuous bag-of-words (CBOW).
[src:retrieval-rerankers/sentence-embedding] However, more elaborate solutions based on word vector quantization have also been proposed.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/sentence-embedding] One such approach is the vector of locally aggregated word embeddings (VLAWE), which demonstrated performance improvements in downstream text classification tasks.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/sentence-embedding] In recent years, sentence embedding has seen a growing level of interest due to its applications in natural language queryable knowledge bases through the usage of vector indexing for semantic search.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/sentence-embedding] LangChain for instance utilizes sentence transformers for purposes of indexing documents.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/sentence-embedding] In particular, an indexing is generated by generating embeddings for chunks of documents and storing (document chunk, embedding) tuples.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/sentence-embedding] Then given a query in natural language, the embedding for the query can be generated.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/sentence-embedding] A top k similarity search algorithm is then used between the query embedding and the document chunk embeddings to retrieve the most relevant document chunks as context information for question answering tasks.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/sentence-embedding] This approach is also known formally as retrieval-augmented generation.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/sentence-embedding] Though not as predominant as BERTScore, sentence embeddings are commonly used for sentence similarity evaluation which sees common use for the task of optimizing a Large language model's generation parameters is often performed via comparing candidate sentences against reference sentences.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/sentence-embedding] By using the cosine-similarity of the sentence embeddings of candidate and reference sentences as the evaluation function, a grid-search algorithm can be utilized to automate hyperparameter optimization.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/sentence-embedding] Multiple approaches exists for evaluating the quality of sentence embeddings typically covering one or multiple of the use-cases on models.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/sentence-embedding] Some seek to measure whether the embedding is semantically meaningful by testing if semantically similar sentences appear closer together, while other sentence similarity or if embeddings reflect entailment using corpora such as Sentences Involving Compositional Knowledge (SICK), STS Bencmark.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/sentence-embedding] Other approaches seek to measure the quality of the embeddings by how well it performs for downstream use-cases such as clustering, classification or semantic search.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/sentence-embedding] Comprehensive frameworks such as BEIR or MTEB that encapsulates multiple of these approaches have since become the standard to evaluate the quality of embedding across domains and/or languages.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/vector-database] A **vector database**, **vector store** or **vector search engine** is a database that stores and retrieves embeddings of data in vector space.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/vector-database] Vector databases typically implement approximate nearest neighbor algorithms so users can search for records semantically similar to a given input, unlike traditional databases which primarily look up records by exact match.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/vector-database] Use-cases for vector databases include similarity search, semantic search, multi-modal search, recommendations engines, object detection, and retrieval-augmented generation (RAG).
[src:retrieval-rerankers/vector-database] Vector embeddings are mathematical representations of data in a high-dimensional space.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/vector-database] In this space, each dimension corresponds to a feature of the data, with the number of dimensions ranging from a few hundred to tens of thousands, depending on the complexity of the data being represented.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/vector-database] Each data item is represented by one vector in this space.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/vector-database] Words, phrases, or entire documents, as well as images, audio, and other types of data, can all be vectorized.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/vector-database] These feature vectors may be computed from the raw data using machine learning methods such as feature extraction algorithms, word embeddings or deep learning networks.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/vector-database] The goal is that semantically similar data items receive feature vectors close to each other.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/vector-database] Vector retrieval can be combined with metadata filtering or lexical search to support filtered and hybrid retrieval workflows.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/vector-database] These techniques may also be combined in vector search systems.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/vector-database] In recent benchmarks, HNSW-based implementations have been among the best performers.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/vector-database] Conferences such as the International Conference on Similarity Search and Applications (SISAP) and the Conference on Neural Information Processing Systems (NeurIPS) have hosted competitions on vector search in large databases.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/vector-database] Vector databases are used in a wide range of machine learning applications including similarity search, semantic search, multi-modal search, recommendations engines, object detection, and retrieval-augmented generation.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/vector-database] An especially common use-case for vector databases is in retrieval-augmented generation (RAG), a method to improve domain-specific responses of large language models.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/vector-database] The retrieval component of a RAG can be any search system, but is most often implemented as a vector database.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/vector-database] Text documents describing the domain of interest are collected, and for each document or document section, a feature vector (known as an "embedding") is computed, typically using a deep learning network, and stored in a vector database along with a link to the document.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/vector-database] Given a user prompt, the feature vector of the prompt is computed, and the database is queried to retrieve the most relevant documents.
[src:retrieval-rerankers/vector-database] These are then automatically added into the context window of the large language model, and the large language model proceeds to create a response to the prompt given this context.
